The paper focuses on using deep learning techniques for image analysis in the context of drug discovery. Specifically, it uses pre-trained convolutional image features to reduce the dimensionality of raw fluorescent stained images from a high throughput imaging (HTI) screen, producing an embedding space that groups together images with similar cellular phenotypes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses unsupervised clustering to identify distinct phenotypic clusters, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the validation of the embedding space, which suggests that it may belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses deep learning techniques, which suggests that it may also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
